LABORATORY
Her EKG today showed sinus rhythm with marked sinus arrhythmia, first-degree AV block, left axis deviation, and no specific intraventricular conduction delay.  Her chest x-ray showed cardiomegaly with pulmonary venous hypertension.  She had an echocardiogram which showed mild left ventricular enlargement.  No regional wall motion abnormalities.  Ejection fraction of 54%.  Increased left ventricular filling pressure, and her estimated right ventricular systolic pressure was 79.  There was mild decrease in her right ventricular systolic function with RIMP of 0.57 and TAPSE of 17.
Her BUN was 25, creatinine 1.3, glucose 148, hemoglobin 11.8, PT 10, INR 1, calcium 9.6, NT-Pro BNP 723, TSH 2.7.
ASSESSMENT/PLAN
#1 Recently-diagnosed adenocarcinoma of the colon
The patient is scheduled to be seen by Dr. Holland.  We feel the patient has significant risk from this surgery. However, her risks are acknowledged as significant stemming from obesity, hypoxemia, pulmonary hypertension, and coronary artery disease. I have not recommended pursuing evaluation of myocardial ischemia since she does not have compelling symptoms and therapeutic alternatives would be limited in order to avoid clopidogrel. Her pulmonary hypertension may have regressed somewhat but overall is essentially stable of moderate degree. It will be important to manage her volume status carefully during the perioperative period and to maintain adequate oxygenation. If necessary nitric oxide could be employed if there was suspicion that her pulmonary hemodynamics had deteriorated though I do not think that extended intervascular PA pressure monitoring should be necessary. We feel that the patient can have the surgery done.  Volume overload and pressure overload to be avoided in the perioperative period and to watch out for perioperative myocardial ischemia.
#2 Pulmonary hypertension which may be idiopathic but is compounded by her obesity, previous evidence of nocturnal hypoventilation, hypertensive left heart disease with elevated left filling pressure
We will continue her sildenafil at the same dose.
#3 Coronary artery disease
She is on appropriate medication for her coronary disease including aspirin, lisinopril, and simvastatin.
#4 Status-post percutaneous coronary intervention of distal left anterior descending lesion in 2007
#5 Systemic hypertension
#6 History of hyperparathyroidism, status-post left lower parathyroidectomy in August 2009
Case discussed with Dr. Jones

