[start section id="20103"]

Seventy-four-year-old lady with past medical history significant for morbid obesity, history of idiopathic pulmonary arterial hypertension that was treated initially with IV treprostinil which was tolerated poorly, and patient was switched to sildenafil.  She is still taking it at the present time.  She had a past medical history significant of coronary artery disease, status-post stent placement on March 19, 2007.  She had a coronary angiogram done in November 2008, which showed that patient had 60% obtuse marginal stenosis, proximal 50% right coronary artery stenosis, and a 30% middle left anterior descending artery stenosis.  Her estimated right ventricular systolic pressure by ECHO was 51 in July 2009.  The right ventricular systolic pressure by ECHO was 79 today, and her TAPSE was 17.  Ms. Sharer was seen by her primary-care physician in December 2009 and was diagnosed with anemia for which she was placed on iron supplement.  Later she developed bloody diarrhea, and when she informed her primary-care physician, a colonoscopy was arranged and done on March 15, 2010. Colonoscopy showed ulcerating mass in the cecum.  Pathology report revealed adenocarcinoma.  A CT-scan of the abdomen was done and showed no significant metastasis.  The patient is scheduled to see Dr. Holland for further evaluation and to discuss the option for treatment of her colon carcinoma.  The patient is sedentary, and, therefore, it is difficult to judge her functional status, but she states she gets dyspneic when she dresses herself or when she takes a shower.  She is likely stage WHO III in her functional status.  No orthopnea, no syncope, no palpitations, no cough, no fever, no chills.  She has bilateral lower leg edema that has been stable and not increasing.  The patient is supposed to be on continuous oxygen supplement, but she has not been using it for awhile because she feels it did not make her feel any better.  She had a sleep study done on May 19, 2008, which showed obstructive/mixed hypopnea but patient did not have a CPAP, and she was not interested in getting one because she felt uncomfortable when they tried it during the sleep study.  She successfully underwent left inferior parathyroidectomy on August 11, 2009, for hyperparathyroidism, and her calcium has been stable since then.

[end section id="20103"]

